{"questionId":"22641143","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Now consider randomly generated quadratic functions whose corresponding graphs have two <strong>distinct</strong> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-intercepts.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>By considering the discriminant, determine the set of possible values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;In parts (c) – (f),&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>, for example, represents an ordered&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>-tuple&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>recognizes that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> (or equivalent eg. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></math>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p>maximum value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn></math> OR maximum value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(A1)</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The above <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em> is independent of the <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>8</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong><em>[3 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22641143","referenceCode":"24M.3.AHL.TZ2.2d","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"By considering the discriminant, determine the set of possible values of ac.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.7—Solutions of quadratic equations and inequalities, discriminant and nature of roots"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}